    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm studying for my culinary chem exam and i'm a bit stuck on the maillard reaction. can you explain what actually happens chemically when bread crust browns and what kind of temps i need to look out for?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a chemical process where amino acids from proteins react with reducing sugars to form brown pigments called melanoidins and various flavor compounds. This browning typically occurs between 140°C and 165°C (285°F–330°F), though it can start as low as 110°C (230°F) depending on pH and moisture levels. In baking, you want to aim for around 175°C (350°F) to ensure the crust browns nicely before the interior overcooks. If the temperature gets too high, the reaction shifts toward caramelization of sugars or burning, which can alter the texture negatively.",
      "source": "target",
