    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that's helpful. i also saw something in my textbook about how the reaction can be \"unpredictable\" or harder to control if the moisture isn't right. can you explain why the water content in the dough matters so much for the reaction? like, why does it prevent it from happening too fast?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Water acts as a heat sink, absorbing thermal energy and keeping the surface temperature of the dough below the critical threshold needed to initiate the Maillard reaction. Since the reaction rates are highly temperature-dependent, any excess moisture delays the onset of browning, forcing the baker to either increase the oven temperature or extend the baking time. Once the surface moisture evaporates, the temperature can finally rise high enough for the chemical interaction between amino acids and sugars to proceed rapidly. This is why a dry, crisp crust forms quickly but a wet one may stay pale or soggy for a long time.",
