      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction generates over 300 distinct volatile compounds, but the most notable include pyrazines (which provide nutty and roasted flavors), pyridines (adding savory, meaty notes), and pyrroles (contributing to ham-like or mushroomy aromas). It also produces aldehydes and ketones that add fruity or caramel-like nuances, while sulfur-containing compounds like hydrogen sulfide can create distinct umami notes similar to those found in aged cheeses or cured meats. These complex molecules work synergistically to create the rich, savory depth that distinguishes a well-baked crust from a plain, white one.",
